I think a lot about the millennials who were the last generation to be able to connect with artists without the pressure of having a critical eye.
We arrived during the golden age of media, with a collective consciousness of popular culture that no longer exists.
It plunged directly into things without having to worry about the source, because it wasn't so easy to determine.
Without reason to question the pedestal on which we placed them, parasocial relationships had become the foundation of our lives.
That's why we're so attached to nostalgia.
When The Office was still on, my friends and I would order pizzas and watch the series every Thursday.
It resembled nothing like what we have now with streaming, where 12 episodes are available all at once and where everyone watches at their own pace, starting social media posts with "spoiler alert" or continuing in specifically designated closed spaces.
Subconsciously, I couldn't help but feel an envy to connect with the universal community that surrounded everything.
That's why so many of us watch obsessively series like The Office or films like Présentateur vedette, full of short references, like memes.
We were repeating these references, knowing that most people knew them.
Now, even when something becomes completely viral, we can't know if everyone saw it.
There are too many things to see and no way to rationalize them all... will we escape the hypersaturation?
We get caught up in cycles of discovering new media, only to realize that the artist is a predator or a fanatic.
We are forced to deal with a situation where we cling to nostalgia while recognizing that the people who created the art we connect to can be very flawed.
We enter into parasocial relationships by paying more attention.
We understand that it's hard to reach these positions of wealth and power without stepping on others along the way.
Lack of collective consciousness on the media has led us to develop a class consciousness that helps us stay critical.
Some of us continue to put people on a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall.
We are in a tumultuous period and I'm eager to know where it will take us.
Inclusion and safety should be the norm.
